NIOHTTP1 and projectsuserswork around security headers and HTTP/1.1 framing headers using it for generating HTTP responses can be subject to a HTTP Response Injection attack. This occurs when a HTTP/1.1 server accepts user generated input from an incoming request and reflects it into a HTTP/1.1 response header in some form. A malicious user can add newlines to their input (usually in encoded form) and ""inject"" those newlines into the returned HTTP response.
